# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: interpolation-methods
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In geometry, a **barycentric coordinate system** is a coordinate system in which the location of a point is specified by reference to a simplex (a triangle for points in a plane, a tetrahedron for points in three-dimensional space, etc.).
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The **barycentric coordinates** of a point can be interpreted as masses placed at the vertices of the simplex, such that the point is the center of mass (or *barycenter*) of these masses.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] These masses can be zero or negative; they are all positive if and only if the point is strictly inside the simplex.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Every point has barycentric coordinates, and their sum is never zero.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Two tuples of barycentric coordinates specify the same point if and only if they are proportional; that is to say, if one tuple can be obtained by multiplying the elements of the other tuple by the same non-zero number.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Therefore, barycentric coordinates are either considered to be defined up to multiplication by a nonzero constant, or normalized for summing to unity.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric coordinates were introduced by August Möbius in 1827.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] They are special homogeneous coordinates.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric coordinates are strongly related with Cartesian coordinates and, more generally, to affine coordinates ().
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric coordinates are particularly useful in triangle geometry for studying properties that do not depend on the angles of the triangle, such as Ceva's theorem, Routh's theorem, and Menelaus's theorem.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In computer-aided design, they are useful for defining some kinds of Bézier surfaces.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Let $A_{0},\ldots ,A_{n}$ be *n* + 1 points in a Euclidean space, a flat or an affine space $\mathbf {A}$ of dimension n that are affinely independent; this means that there is no affine subspace of dimension *n* − 1 that contains all the points, or, equivalently that the points define a simplex.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Moreover, the barycentric coordinates are also not changed if the auxiliary point O, the origin, is changed.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The barycentric coordinates of a point are unique up to a scaling.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] That is, two tuples $(a_{0}:\dotsc :a_{n})$ and $(b_{0}:\dotsc :b_{n})$ are barycentric coordinates of the same point if and only if there is a nonzero scalar $\lambda$ such that $b_{i}=\lambda a_{i}$ for every i.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In some contexts, it is useful to constrain the barycentric coordinates of a point so that they are unique.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] This is usually achieved by imposing the condition $\sum a_{i}=1,$ or equivalently by dividing every $a_{i}$ by the sum of all $a_{i}.$ These specific barycentric coordinates are called **normalized** or **absolute barycentric coordinates**.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Sometimes, they are also called affine coordinates, although this term refers commonly to a slightly different concept.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Sometimes, it is the normalized barycentric coordinates that are called *barycentric coordinates*.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In this case the above defined coordinates are called *homogeneous barycentric coordinates*.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] With above notation, the homogeneous barycentric coordinates of Ai are all zero, except the one of index i.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] When working over the real numbers (the above definition is also used for affine spaces over an arbitrary field), the points whose all normalized barycentric coordinates are nonnegative form the convex hull of $\{A_{0},\ldots ,A_{n}\},$ which is the simplex that has these points as its vertices.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] With above notation, a tuple $(a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n})$ such that $\sum _{i=0}^{n}a_{i}=0$ does not define any point, but the vector $a_{0}{\overset {}{\overrightarrow {OA_{0}}}}+\cdots +a_{n}{\overset {}{\overrightarrow {OA_{n}}}}$ is independent from the origin O.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] As the direction of this vector is not changed if all $a_{i}$ are multiplied by the same scalar, the homogeneous tuple $(a_{0}:\dotsc :a_{n})$ defines a direction of lines, that is a point at infinity.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric coordinates are strongly related to Cartesian coordinates and, more generally, affine coordinates.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] For a space of dimension n, these coordinate systems are defined relative to a point O, the origin, whose coordinates are zero, and n points $A_{1},\ldots ,A_{n},$ whose coordinates are zero except that of index i that equals one.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The main advantage of barycentric coordinate systems is to be symmetric with respect to the *n* + 1 defining points.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] They are therefore often useful for studying properties that are symmetric with respect to *n* + 1 points.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] On the other hand, distances and angles are difficult to express in general barycentric coordinate systems, and when they are involved, it is generally simpler to use a Cartesian coordinate system.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Homogeneous barycentric coordinates are also strongly related with some projective coordinates.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] However this relationship is more subtle than in the case of affine coordinates, and, for being clearly understood, requires a coordinate-free definition of the projective completion of an affine space, and a definition of a projective frame.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The *projective completion* of an affine space of dimension n is a projective space of the same dimension that contains the affine space as the complement of a hyperplane.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The projective completion is unique up to an isomorphism.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The hyperplane is called the hyperplane at infinity, and its points are the points at infinity of the affine space.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Given a projective space of dimension n, a *projective frame* is an ordered set of *n* + 2 points that are not contained in the same hyperplane.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] A projective frame defines a projective coordinate system such that the coordinates of the (*n* + 2)th point of the frame are all equal, and, otherwise, all coordinates of the ith point are zero, except the ith one.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] This implies that the points at infinity have their last coordinate equal to zero, and that the projective coordinates of a point of the affine space are obtained by completing its affine coordinates by one as (*n* + 1)th coordinate.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] When one has *n* + 1 points in an affine space that define a barycentric coordinate system, this is another projective frame of the projective completion that is convenient to choose.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] This frame consists of these points and their centroid, that is the point that has all its barycentric coordinates equal.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In this case, the homogeneous barycentric coordinates of a point in the affine space are the same as the projective coordinates of this point.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] A point is at infinity if and only if the sum of its coordinates is zero.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] This point is in the direction of the vector defined at the end of § Definition.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Areal and trilinear coordinates are used for similar purposes in geometry.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric or areal coordinates are extremely useful in engineering applications involving triangular subdomains.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] These make analytic integrals often easier to evaluate, and Gaussian quadrature tables are often presented in terms of area coordinates.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] One may regard points in $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ as vectors, so it makes sense to add or subtract them and multiply them by scalars.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The sign is plus if the path from A to B to C then back to A goes around the triangle in a counterclockwise direction.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The sign is minus if the path goes around in a clockwise direction.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] One may prove these ratio formulas based on the facts that a triangle is half of a parallelogram, and the area of a parallelogram is easy to compute using a determinant.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] $ABCD$ is a parallelogram because its pairs of opposite sides, represented by the pairs of displacement vectors $D-C=B-A$ , and $D-B=C-A$ , are parallel and congruent.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Trilinear coordinates $(\gamma _{1},\gamma _{2},\gamma _{3})$ of P are signed distances from P to the lines BC, AC, and AB, respectively.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The sign of $\gamma _{1}$ is positive if P and A lie on the same side of BC, negative otherwise.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The signs of $\gamma _{2}$ and $\gamma _{3}$ are assigned similarly.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] where, as above, sarea stands for signed area.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] All three signs are plus if triangle ABC is positively oriented, minus otherwise.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The relations between trilinear and barycentric coordinates are obtained by substituting these formulas into the above formulas that express barycentric coordinates as ratios of areas.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Switching back and forth between the barycentric coordinates and other coordinate systems makes some problems much easier to solve.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Given a point $\mathbf {r}$ in a triangle's plane one can obtain the barycentric coordinates $\lambda _{1}$ , $\lambda _{2}$ and $\lambda _{3}$ from the Cartesian coordinates $(x,y)$ or vice versa.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] That is, the Cartesian coordinates of any point are a weighted average of the Cartesian coordinates of the triangle's vertices, with the weights being the point's barycentric coordinates summing to unity.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Now the matrix $\mathbf {T}$ is invertible, since $\mathbf {r} _{1}-\mathbf {r} _{3}$ and $\mathbf {r} _{2}-\mathbf {r} _{3}$ are linearly independent (if this were not the case, then $\mathbf {r} _{1}$ , $\mathbf {r} _{2}$ , and $\mathbf {r} _{3}$ would be collinear and would not form a triangle).
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Finding the barycentric coordinates has thus been reduced to finding the 2×2 inverse matrix of $\mathbf {T}$ , an easy problem.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The area interpretation of the barycentric coordinates can be recovered by applying Cramer's rule to this linear system.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] A point with trilinear coordinates *x* : *y* : *z* has barycentric coordinates *ax* : *by* : *cz* where *a*, *b*, *c* are the side lengths of the triangle.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Using the previously given conversion between barycentric and trilinear coordinates, the various other equations given in Trilinear coordinates#Formulas can be rewritten in terms of barycentric coordinates.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] where *a, b, c* are the sidelengths of the triangle.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Although barycentric coordinates are most commonly used to handle points inside a triangle, they can also be used to describe a point outside the triangle.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] If the point is not inside the triangle, then we can still use the formulas above to compute the barycentric coordinates.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] However, since the point is outside the triangle, at least one of the coordinates will violate our original assumption that $\lambda _{1...3}\geq 0$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In fact, given any point in cartesian coordinates, we can use this fact to determine where this point is with respect to a triangle.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Finally, if the point lies outside the triangle at least one coordinate is negative.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In particular, if a point lies on the far side of a line the barycentric coordinate of the point in the triangle that is not on the line will have a negative value.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] If $f(\mathbf {r} _{1}),f(\mathbf {r} _{2}),f(\mathbf {r} _{3})$ are known quantities, but the values of f inside the triangle defined by $\mathbf {r} _{1},\mathbf {r} _{2},\mathbf {r} _{3}$ is unknown, they can be approximated using linear interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric coordinates provide a convenient way to compute this interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In general, given any unstructured grid or polygon mesh, this kind of technique can be used to approximate the value of f at all points, as long as the function's value is known at all vertices of the mesh.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In this case, we have many triangles, each corresponding to a different part of the space.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] To interpolate a function f at a point $\mathbf {r}$ , first a triangle must be found that contains $\mathbf {r}$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] To do so, $\mathbf {r}$ is transformed into the barycentric coordinates of each triangle.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] If some triangle is found such that the coordinates satisfy $0\leq \lambda _{i}\leq 1\;\forall \;i{\text{ in }}1,2,3$ , then the point lies in that triangle or on its edge (explained in the previous section).
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Then the value of $f(\mathbf {r} )$ can be interpolated as described above.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] These methods have many applications, such as the finite element method (FEM).
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The integral of a function over the domain of the triangle can be annoying to compute in a cartesian coordinate system.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] One generally has to split the triangle up into two halves, and great messiness follows.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Instead, it is often easier to make a change of variables to any two barycentric coordinates, e.g. $\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2}$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] This result follows from the fact that a rectangle in barycentric coordinates corresponds to a quadrilateral in cartesian coordinates, and the ratio of the areas of the corresponding shapes in the corresponding coordinate systems is given by $2A$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] This approach can be generalized to higher dimensions, to integrate over any n-dimensional simplex.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In the homogeneous barycentric coordinate system defined with respect to a triangle $ABC$ , the following statements about special points of $ABC$ hold.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] If a, b, c are the edge lengths $BC$ , $CA$ , $AB$ respectively, $\alpha$ , $\beta$ , $\gamma$ are the angle measures $\angle CAB$ , $\angle ABC$ , and $\angle BCA$ respectively, and s is the semiperimeter of $ABC$ , then the following statements about special points of $ABC$ hold in addition.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The Nagel point has coordinates $s-a:s-b:s-c$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric coordinates may be easily extended to three dimensions.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The 3D simplex is a tetrahedron, a polyhedron having four triangular faces and four vertices.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Once again, the four barycentric coordinates are defined so that the first vertex $\mathbf {r} _{1}$ maps to barycentric coordinates $\lambda =(1,0,0,0)$ , $\mathbf {r} _{2}\to (0,1,0,0)$ , etc.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] 3D barycentric coordinates may be used to decide if a point lies inside a tetrahedral volume, and to interpolate a function within a tetrahedral mesh, in an analogous manner to the 2D procedure.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Tetrahedral meshes are often used in finite element analysis because the use of barycentric coordinates can greatly simplify 3D interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric coordinates $(\lambda _{1},\lambda _{2},...,\lambda _{k})$ of a point $p\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ that are defined with respect to a finite set of *k* points $x_{1},x_{2},...,x_{k}\in \mathbb {R} ^{n}$ instead of a simplex are called **generalized barycentric coordinates**.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Usually one uses normalized coordinates, $\lambda _{1}+\lambda _{2}+\cdots +\lambda _{k}=1$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] As for the case of a simplex, the points with nonnegative normalized generalized coordinates ( $0\leq \lambda _{i}\leq 1$ ) form the convex hull of *x*1, ..., *x**n*.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] The simplest example is a quadrilateral in the plane.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Various kinds of additional restrictions can be used to define unique barycentric coordinates.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Dual to generalized barycentric coordinates are slack variables, which measure by how much margin a point satisfies the linear constraints, and gives an embedding $P\hookrightarrow (\mathbf {R} _{\geq 0})^{f}$ into the *f*-orthant, where *f* is the number of faces (dual to the vertices).
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] This map is one-to-one (slack variables are uniquely determined) but not onto (not all combinations can be realized).
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Further, the *n*-orthant is the standard object that maps *to* cones.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Generalized barycentric coordinates have applications in computer graphics and more specifically in geometric modelling.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Often, a three-dimensional model can be approximated by a polyhedron such that the generalized barycentric coordinates with respect to that polyhedron have a geometric meaning.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] In this way, the processing of the model can be simplified by using these meaningful coordinates.
[src:interpolation-methods/barycentric-coordinate-system] Barycentric coordinates are also used in geophysics.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] In mathematics, **bilinear interpolation** is a method for interpolating functions of two variables (e.g., *x* and *y*) using repeated linear interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] It is usually applied to functions sampled on a 2D rectilinear grid, though it can be generalized to functions defined on the vertices of (a mesh of) arbitrary convex quadrilaterals.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Bilinear interpolation is performed using linear interpolation first in one direction, and then again in another direction.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Although each step is linear in the sampled values and in the position, the interpolation as a whole is not linear but rather quadratic in the sample location.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Bilinear interpolation is one of the basic resampling techniques in computer vision and image processing, where it is also called **bilinear filtering** or **bilinear texture mapping**.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Suppose that we want to find the value of the unknown function *f* at the point (*x*, *y*).
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] We first do linear interpolation in the *x*-direction.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Note that we will arrive at the same result if the interpolation is done first along the *y* direction and then along the *x* direction.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] in agreement with the result obtained by repeated linear interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] The set of weights can also be interpreted as a set of generalized barycentric coordinates for a rectangle.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] In both cases, the number of constants (four) correspond to the number of data points where *f* is given.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] As the name suggests, the bilinear interpolant is *not* linear; but it is linear (i.e. affine) along lines parallel to either the *x* or the *y* direction, equivalently if *x* or *y* is held constant.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Along any other straight line, the interpolant is quadratic.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Even though the interpolation is *not* linear in the position (*x* and *y*), at a fixed point it *is* linear in the interpolation values, as can be seen in the (matrix) equations above.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] The result of bilinear interpolation is independent of which axis is interpolated first and which second.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] If we had first performed the linear interpolation in the *y* direction and then in the *x* direction, the resulting approximation would be the same.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] The interpolant is a bilinear polynomial, which is also a harmonic function satisfying Laplace's equation.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Its graph is a bilinear Bézier surface patch.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] In general, the interpolant will assume any value (in the convex hull of the vertex values) at an infinite number of points (forming branches of hyperbolas), so the interpolation is not invertible.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] However, when bilinear interpolation is applied to two functions simultaneously, such as when interpolating a vector field, then the interpolation is invertible (under certain conditions).
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] In particular, this inverse can be used to find the "unit square coordinates" of a point inside any convex quadrilateral (by considering the coordinates of the quadrilateral as a vector field which is bilinearly interpolated on the unit square).
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Using this procedure bilinear interpolation can be extended to any convex quadrilateral, though the computation is significantly more complicated if it is not a parallelogram.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] The resulting map between quadrilaterals is known as a *bilinear transformation*, *bilinear warp* or *bilinear distortion*.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Alternatively, a projective mapping between a quadrilateral and the unit square may be used, but the resulting interpolant will not be bilinear.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] In the special case when the quadrilateral is a parallelogram, a linear mapping to the unit square exists and the generalization follows easily.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] The obvious extension of bilinear interpolation to three dimensions is called trilinear interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] In computer vision and image processing, bilinear interpolation is used to resample images and textures.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] An algorithm is used to map a screen pixel location to a corresponding point on the texture map.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] A weighted average of the attributes (color, transparency, etc.) of the four surrounding texels is computed and applied to the screen pixel.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] This process is repeated for each pixel forming the object being textured.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] When an image needs to be scaled up, each pixel of the original image needs to be moved in a certain direction based on the scale constant.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] However, when scaling up an image by a non-integral scale factor, there are pixels (i.e., *holes*) that are not assigned appropriate pixel values.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] In this case, those *holes* should be assigned appropriate RGB or grayscale values so that the output image does not have non-valued pixels.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Bilinear interpolation can be used where perfect image transformation with pixel matching is impossible, so that one can calculate and assign appropriate intensity values to pixels.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Unlike other interpolation techniques such as nearest-neighbor interpolation and bicubic interpolation, bilinear interpolation uses values of only the 4 nearest pixels, located in diagonal directions from a given pixel, in order to find the appropriate color intensity values of that pixel.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Bilinear interpolation considers the closest 2 × 2 neighborhood of known pixel values surrounding the unknown pixel's computed location.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] It then takes a weighted average of these 4 pixels to arrive at its final, interpolated value.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] This algorithm reduces some of the visual distortion caused by resizing an image to a non-integral zoom factor, as opposed to nearest-neighbor interpolation, which will make some pixels appear larger than others in the resized image.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] These repetitions can be assigned temporary variables whilst computing a single interpolation, which will reduce the number of operations to 19.
[src:interpolation-methods/bilinear-interpolation] Simplification of terms is good practice for application of mathematical methodology to engineering applications and can reduce computational and energy requirements for a process.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **interpolation** is a type of estimation, a method of constructing (finding) new data points based on the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In engineering and science, one often has a number of data points, obtained by sampling or experimentation, which represent the values of a function for a limited number of values of the independent variable.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] It is often required to **interpolate**; that is, estimate the value of that function for an intermediate value of the independent variable.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] A closely related problem is the approximation of a complicated function by a simple function.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Suppose the formula for some given function is known, but too complicated to evaluate efficiently.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] A few data points from the original function can be interpolated to produce a simpler function which is still fairly close to the original.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The resulting gain in simplicity may outweigh the loss from interpolation error and give better performance in calculation process.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] As an example we will use points from the equation $f(x)=sin(x)$ to demonstrate various interpolation methods.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] We describe some methods of interpolation, differing in such properties as: accuracy, cost, number of data points needed, and smoothness of the resulting interpolant function.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The simplest interpolation method is to locate the nearest data value, and assign the same value.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In simple problems, this method is unlikely to be used, as linear interpolation (see below) is almost as easy, but in higher-dimensional multivariate interpolation, this could be a favourable choice for its speed and simplicity.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] One of the simplest methods is linear interpolation (sometimes known as lerp).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Consider the above example of estimating *f*(2.5).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Linear interpolation is quick and easy, but it is not very precise.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Another disadvantage is that the interpolant is not differentiable at the point *x**k*.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The following error estimate shows that linear interpolation is not very precise.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Denote the function which we want to interpolate by *g*, and suppose that *x* lies between *x**a* and *x**b* and that *g* is twice continuously differentiable.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In words, the error is proportional to the square of the distance between the data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The error in some other methods, including polynomial interpolation and spline interpolation (described below), is proportional to higher powers of the distance between the data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] These methods also produce smoother interpolants.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation is a generalization of linear interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Note that the linear interpolant is a linear function.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] We now replace this interpolant with a polynomial of higher degree.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Generally, if we have *n* data points, there is exactly one polynomial of degree at most *n*−1 going through all the data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The interpolation error is proportional to the distance between the data points to the power *n*.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Furthermore, the interpolant is a polynomial and thus infinitely differentiable.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] So, we see that polynomial interpolation overcomes most of the problems of linear interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] However, polynomial interpolation also has some disadvantages.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Calculating the interpolating polynomial is computationally expensive (see computational complexity) compared to linear interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Furthermore, polynomial interpolation may exhibit oscillatory artifacts, especially at the end points (see Runge's phenomenon).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Polynomial interpolation can estimate local maxima and minima that are outside the range of the samples, unlike linear interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] However, these maxima and minima may exceed the theoretical range of the function; for example, a function that is always positive may have an interpolant with negative values, and whose inverse therefore contains false vertical asymptotes.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] More generally, the shape of the resulting curve, especially for very high or low values of the independent variable, may be contrary to commonsense; that is, to what is known about the experimental system which has generated the data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] These disadvantages can be reduced by using spline interpolation or restricting attention to Chebyshev polynomials.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Linear interpolation uses a linear function for each of intervals [*x**k*,*x**k+1*].
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Spline interpolation uses low-degree polynomials in each of the intervals, and chooses the polynomial pieces such that they fit smoothly together.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The resulting function is called a spline.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] For instance, the natural cubic spline is piecewise cubic and twice continuously differentiable.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Furthermore, its second derivative is zero at the end points.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Like polynomial interpolation, spline interpolation incurs a smaller error than linear interpolation, while the interpolant is smoother and easier to evaluate than the high-degree polynomials used in polynomial interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] However, the global nature of the basis functions leads to ill-conditioning.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] This is completely mitigated by using splines of compact support, such as are implemented in Boost.Math and discussed in Kress.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Depending on the underlying discretisation of fields, different interpolants may be required.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In contrast to other interpolation methods, which estimate functions on target points, mimetic interpolation evaluates the integral of fields on target lines, areas or volumes, depending on the type of field (scalar, vector, pseudo-vector or pseudo-scalar).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] A key feature of mimetic interpolation is that vector calculus identities are satisfied, including Stokes' theorem and the divergence theorem.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] As a result, mimetic interpolation conserves line, area and volume integrals.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Conservation of line integrals might be desirable when interpolating the electric field, for instance, since the line integral gives the electric potential difference at the endpoints of the integration path.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation ensures that the error of estimating the line integral of an electric field is the same as the error obtained by interpolating the potential at the end points of the integration path, regardless of the length of the integration path.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Linear, bilinear and trilinear interpolation are also considered mimetic, even if it is the field values that are conserved (not the integral of the field).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Apart from linear interpolation, area weighted interpolation can be considered one of the first mimetic interpolation methods to have been developed.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The Theory of Functional Connections (TFC) is a mathematical framework specifically developed for functional interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Given any interpolant that satisfies a set of constraints, TFC derives a functional that represents the entire family of interpolants satisfying those constraints, including those that are discontinuous or partially defined.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] These functionals identify the subspace of functions where the solution to a constrained optimization problem resides.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Consequently, TFC transforms constrained optimization problems into equivalent unconstrained formulations.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] This transformation has proven highly effective in the solution of differential equations.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] TFC achieves this by constructing a constrained functional (a function of a free function), that inherently satisfies given constraints regardless of the expression of the free function.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] This simplifies solving various types of equations and significantly improves the efficiency and accuracy of methods like Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] TFC offers advantages over traditional methods like Lagrange multipliers and spectral methods by directly addressing constraints analytically and avoiding iterative procedures, although it cannot currently handle inequality constraints.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Interpolation is a common way to approximate functions.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Given a function $f:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ with a set of points $x_{1},x_{2},\dots ,x_{n}\in [a,b]$ one can form a function $s:[a,b]\to \mathbb {R}$ such that $f(x_{i})=s(x_{i})$ for $i=1,2,\dots ,n$ (that is, that s interpolates f at these points).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In general, an interpolant need not be a good approximation, but there are well known and often reasonable conditions where it will.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] For example, if $f\in C^{4}([a,b])$ (four times continuously differentiable) then cubic spline interpolation has an error bound given by $\|f-s\|_{\infty }\leq C\|f^{(4)}\|_{\infty }h^{4}$ where $h\max _{i=1,2,\dots ,n-1}|x_{i+1}-x_{i}|$ and C is a constant.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Gaussian process is a powerful non-linear interpolation tool.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Many popular interpolation tools are actually equivalent to particular Gaussian processes.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Gaussian processes can be used not only for fitting an interpolant that passes exactly through the given data points but also for regression; that is, for fitting a curve through noisy data.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In the geostatistics community Gaussian process regression is also known as Kriging.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Inverse Distance Weighting (IDW) is a spatial interpolation method that estimates values based on nearby data points, with closer points having more influence.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] It uses an inverse power law for weighting, where higher power values emphasize local effects, while lower values create a smoother surface.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] IDW is widely used in GIS, meteorology, and environmental modeling for its simplicity but may produce artifacts in clustered or uneven data.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Other forms of interpolation can be constructed by picking a different class of interpolants.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] For instance, rational interpolation is **interpolation** by rational functions using Padé approximant, and trigonometric interpolation is interpolation by trigonometric polynomials using Fourier series.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula can be used if the number of data points is infinite or if the function to be interpolated has compact support.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Sometimes, we know not only the value of the function that we want to interpolate, at some points, but also its derivative.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] This leads to Hermite interpolation problems.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] When each data point is itself a function, it can be useful to see the interpolation problem as a partial advection problem between each data point.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] This idea leads to the displacement interpolation problem used in transportation theory.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Multivariate interpolation is the interpolation of functions of more than one variable.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Methods include nearest-neighbor interpolation, bilinear interpolation and bicubic interpolation in two dimensions, and trilinear interpolation in three dimensions.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] They can be applied to gridded or scattered data.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Mimetic interpolation generalizes to n dimensional spaces where $n>3$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In this application there is a specific requirement that the harmonic content of the original signal be preserved without creating aliased harmonic content of the original signal above the original Nyquist limit of the signal (that is, above fs/2 of the original signal sample rate).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] An early and fairly elementary discussion on this subject can be found in Rabiner and Crochiere's book *Multirate Digital Signal Processing*.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The term *extrapolation* is used to find data points outside the range of known data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In curve fitting problems, the constraint that the interpolant has to go exactly through the data points is relaxed.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] It is only required to approach the data points as closely as possible (within some other constraints).
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] This requires parameterizing the potential interpolants and having some way of measuring the error.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] In the simplest case this leads to least squares approximation.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] Approximation theory studies how to find the best approximation to a given function by another function from some predetermined class, and how good this approximation is.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] This clearly yields a bound on how well the interpolant can approximate the unknown function.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] If we consider x as a variable in a topological space, and the function $f(x)$ mapping to a Banach space, then the problem is treated as "interpolation of operators".
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] The classical results about interpolation of operators are the Riesz–Thorin theorem and the Marcinkiewicz theorem.
[src:interpolation-methods/interpolation] There are also many other subsequent results.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] In numerical analysis, the **Lagrange interpolating polynomial** is the unique polynomial of lowest degree that interpolates a given set of data.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Given a data set of coordinate pairs ⁠ $\textstyle (x_{j},y_{j})$ ⁠, the ⁠ $\textstyle x_{j}$ ⁠ are called *nodes* and the ⁠ $\textstyle y_{j}$ ⁠ are called *values*.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] The Lagrange polynomial ⁠ $L(x)$ ⁠ which interpolates the data assumes each value at the corresponding node, ⁠ $\textstyle L(x_{j})=y_{j}$ ⁠.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] If there are ⁠ $k+1$ ⁠ data pairs, the Lagrange polynomial has degree ⁠ $\leq k$ ⁠.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Although named after Joseph-Louis Lagrange, who published it in 1795, the method was first discovered in 1779 by Edward Waring.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] It is also an easy consequence of a formula published in 1783 by Leonhard Euler.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Uses of Lagrange polynomials include the Newton–Cotes method of numerical integration, Shamir's secret sharing scheme in cryptography, and Reed–Solomon error correction in coding theory.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] For equispaced nodes, Lagrange interpolation is susceptible to Runge's phenomenon of large oscillation.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Using the Kronecker delta this can be written ⁠ $\textstyle \ell _{j}(x_{m})=\delta _{jm}$ ⁠.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Notice that the numerator ⁠ $\textstyle \prod _{m\neq j}(x-x_{m})$ ⁠ has ⁠ k ⁠ roots at the nodes $\textstyle \{x_{m}\}_{m\neq j}$ while the denominator ⁠ $\textstyle \prod _{m\neq j}(x_{j}-x_{m})$ ⁠ scales the resulting polynomial so that ⁠ $\textstyle \ell _{j}(x_{j})=1$ ⁠.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Proof: assume some polynomial ⁠ $M(x)$ ⁠ of degree ⁠ $\leq k$ ⁠ interpolates the data.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] But the only polynomial of degree ⁠ $\leq k$ ⁠ with more than ⁠ k ⁠ roots is the constant zero function, so ⁠ $M(x)-L(x)=0$ ⁠, or ⁠ $M(x)=L(x)$ ⁠.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] If the weights ⁠ $\textstyle w_{j}$ ⁠ have been pre-computed, this requires only ⁠ ${\mathcal {O}}(k)$ ⁠ operations compared to ⁠ $\textstyle {\mathcal {O}}(k^{2})$ ⁠ for evaluating each Lagrange basis polynomial ⁠ $\textstyle \ell _{j}(x)$ ⁠ individually.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] The barycentric interpolation formula can also easily be updated to incorporate a new node ⁠ $\textstyle x_{k+1}$ ⁠ by dividing each of the ⁠ $\textstyle w_{j}$ ⁠, ⁠ $j=0\dots k$ ⁠ by ⁠ $\textstyle (x_{j}-x_{k+1})$ ⁠ and constructing the new ⁠ $\textstyle w_{k+1}$ ⁠ as above.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] This is called the *second form* or *true form* of the barycentric interpolation formula.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Solving an interpolation problem leads to a problem in linear algebra amounting to inversion of a matrix.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Using a standard monomial basis for our interpolation polynomial ${\textstyle L(x)=\sum _{j=0}^{k}x^{j}m_{j}}$ , we must invert the Vandermonde matrix $(x_{i})^{j}$ to solve $L(x_{i})=y_{i}$ for the coefficients $m_{j}$ of $L(x)$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] By choosing a better basis, the Lagrange basis, ${\textstyle L(x)=\sum _{j=0}^{k}l_{j}(x)y_{j}}$ , we merely get the identity matrix, $\delta _{ij}$ , which is its own inverse: the Lagrange basis automatically *inverts* the analog of the Vandermonde matrix.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] This construction is analogous to the Chinese remainder theorem.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Instead of checking for remainders of integers modulo prime numbers, we are checking for remainders of polynomials when divided by linears.
[src:interpolation-methods/lagrange-polynomial] Furthermore, when the order is large, Fast Fourier transformation can be used to solve for the coefficients of the interpolated polynomial.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, a **Newton polynomial**, named after its inventor Isaac Newton, is an interpolation polynomial for a given set of data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The Newton polynomial is sometimes called **Newton's divided differences interpolation polynomial** because the coefficients of the polynomial are calculated using Newton's divided differences method.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The Newton polynomial can be expressed in a simplified form when $x_{0},x_{1},\dots ,x_{k}$ are arranged consecutively with equal spacing.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] This is called the **Newton forward divided difference formula**.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] This is called the **Newton backward divided difference formula**.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Newton's formula is of interest because it is the straightforward and natural differences-version of Taylor's polynomial.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Taylor's polynomial tells where a function will go, based on its ⁠ y ⁠ value, and its derivatives (its rate of change, and the rate of change of its rate of change, etc.) at one particular ⁠ x ⁠ value.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Newton's formula is Taylor's polynomial based on finite differences instead of instantaneous rates of change.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] For a polynomial $p_{n}$ of degree less than or equal to ⁠ n ⁠, that interpolates f at the nodes $x_{i}$ where ⁠ $i=0,1,2,3,\dots ,n$ ⁠.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Let $p_{n+1}$ be the polynomial of degree less than or equal to ⁠ $n+1$ ⁠ that interpolates f at the nodes $x_{i}$ where ⁠ $i=0,1,2,3,\dots ,n,n+1$ ⁠.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] By the uniqueness of interpolated polynomials of degree less than ⁠ $n+1$ ⁠, ${\textstyle p_{n+1}(x)=p_{n}(x)+a_{n+1}w_{n}(x)}$ is the required polynomial interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Thus, Newton polynomials are used to provide polynomial interpolation formula of n points.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] As with other difference formulas, the degree of a Newton interpolating polynomial can be increased by adding more terms and points without discarding existing ones.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Newton's form has the simplicity that the new points are always added at one end: Newton's forward formula can add new points to the right, and Newton's backward formula can add new points to the left.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The accuracy of polynomial interpolation depends on how close the interpolated point is to the middle of the ⁠ x ⁠ values of the set of points used.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Obviously, as new points are added at one end, that middle becomes farther and farther from the first data point.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Therefore, if it isn't known how many points will be needed for the desired accuracy, the middle of the ⁠ x ⁠-values might be far from where the interpolation is done.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Gauss, Stirling, and Bessel all developed formulae to remedy that problem.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Gauss's formula alternately adds new points at the left and right ends, thereby keeping the set of points centered near the same place (near the evaluated point).
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] When so doing, it uses terms from Newton's formula, with data points and ⁠ x ⁠ values renamed in keeping with one's choice of what data point is designated as the ⁠ $x_{0}$ ⁠ data point.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Stirling's formula remains centered about a particular data point, for use when the evaluated point is nearer to a data point than to a middle of two data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Bessel's formula remains centered about a particular middle between two data points, for use when the evaluated point is nearer to a middle than to a data point.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Bessel and Stirling achieve that by sometimes using the average of two differences, and sometimes using the average of two products of binomials in ⁠ x ⁠, where Newton's or Gauss's would use just one difference or product.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Stirling's uses an average difference in odd-degree terms (whose difference uses an even number of data points); Bessel's uses an average difference in even-degree terms (whose difference uses an odd number of data points).
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] For any given finite set of data points, there is only one polynomial of least possible degree that passes through all of them.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Thus, it is appropriate to speak of the "Newton form", or Lagrange form, etc., of the interpolation polynomial.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] However, different methods of computing this polynomial can have differing computational efficiency.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] There are several similar methods, such as those of Gauss, Bessel and Stirling.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] They can be derived from Newton's by renaming the ⁠ x ⁠-values of the data points, but in practice they are important.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The choice between Bessel and Stirling depends on whether the interpolated point is closer to a data point, or closer to a middle between two data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] A polynomial interpolation's error approaches zero, as the interpolation point approaches a data-point.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Therefore, Stirling's formula brings its accuracy improvement where it is least needed and Bessel brings its accuracy improvement where it is most needed.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] So, Bessel's formula could be said to be the most consistently accurate difference formula, and, in general, the most consistently accurate of the familiar polynomial interpolation formulas.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Lagrange is sometimes said to require less work, and is sometimes recommended for problems in which it is known, in advance, from previous experience, how many terms are needed for sufficient accuracy.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The divided difference methods have the advantage that more data points can be added, for improved accuracy.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The terms based on the previous data points can continue to be used.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] With the ordinary Lagrange formula, to do the problem with more data points would require re-doing the whole problem.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] There is a "barycentric" version of Lagrange that avoids the need to re-do the entire calculation when adding a new data point.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] But it requires that the values of each term be recorded.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] But the ability, of Gauss, Bessel and Stirling, to keep the data points centered close to the interpolated point gives them an advantage over Lagrange, when it is not known, in advance, how many data points will be needed.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Additionally, suppose that one wants to find out if, for some particular type of problem, linear interpolation is sufficiently accurate.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] That can be determined by evaluating the quadratic term of a divided difference formula.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] If the quadratic term is negligible—meaning that the linear term is sufficiently accurate without adding the quadratic term—then linear interpolation is sufficiently accurate.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] If the problem is sufficiently important, or if the quadratic term is nearly big enough to matter, then one might want to determine whether the sum of the quadratic and cubic terms is large enough to matter in the problem.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Of course, only a divided-difference method can be used for such a determination.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] For that purpose, the divided-difference formula and/or its ⁠ $x_{0}$ ⁠ point should be chosen so that the formula will use, for its linear term, the two data points between which the linear interpolation of interest would be done.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The divided difference formulas are more versatile, useful in more kinds of problems.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The Lagrange formula is at its best when all the interpolation will be done at one ⁠ x ⁠ value, with only the data points' ⁠ y ⁠ values varying from one problem to another, and when it is known, from past experience, how many terms are needed for sufficient accuracy.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] With the Newton form of the interpolating polynomial a compact and effective algorithm exists for combining the terms to find the coefficients of the polynomial.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] When, with Stirling's or Bessel's, the last term used includes the average of two differences, then one more point is being used than Newton's or other polynomial interpolations would use for the same polynomial degree.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] For the special case of ⁠ $x_{i}=i$ ⁠, there is a closely related set of polynomials, also called the Newton polynomials, that are simply the binomial coefficients for general argument.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] In this form, the Newton polynomials generate the Newton series.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] These are in turn a special case of the general difference polynomials which allow the representation of analytic functions through generalized difference equations.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Solving an interpolation problem leads to a problem in linear algebra where we have to solve a system of linear equations.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Using a standard monomial basis for our interpolation polynomial we get the very complicated Vandermonde matrix.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] By choosing another basis, the Newton basis, we get a system of linear equations with a much simpler lower triangular matrix which can be solved faster.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] to solve the polynomial interpolation problem.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] While the interpolation formula can be found by solving a linear system of equations, there is a loss of intuition in what the formula is showing and why Newton's interpolation formula works is not readily apparent.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Induction step: Suppose the result holds for any divided difference involving at most $n+1$ terms.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] We again prove these statements by induction.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Thus it is the unique polynomial of degree $\leq n$ which passes through these points.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] So we see Newton interpolation permits indeed to add new interpolation points without destroying what has already been computed.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] As can be seen from the definition of the divided differences new data points can be added to the data set to create a new interpolation polynomial without recalculating the old coefficients.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] And when a data point changes we usually do not have to recalculate all coefficients.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Furthermore, if the *x**i* are distributed equidistantly the calculation of the divided differences becomes significantly easier.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Therefore, the divided-difference formulas are usually preferred over the Lagrange form for practical purposes.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] The divided differences can be written in the form of a table.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] For example, for a function ⁠ f ⁠ is to be interpolated on points ⁠ $x_{0},\ldots ,x_{n}$ ⁠.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Then the interpolating polynomial is formed as above using the topmost entries in each column as coefficients.
[src:interpolation-methods/newton-polynomial] Given more digits of accuracy in the table, the first and third coefficients will be found to be zero.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] In numerical analysis, **polynomial interpolation** is the interpolation of a given data set by the polynomial of lowest possible degree that passes through the points in the dataset.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] There is always a unique such polynomial, commonly given by two explicit formulas, the Lagrange polynomials and Newton polynomials.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] The original use of interpolation polynomials was to approximate values of important transcendental functions such as natural logarithm and trigonometric functions.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Starting with a few accurately computed data points, the corresponding interpolation polynomial will approximate the function at an arbitrary nearby point.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Polynomial interpolation also forms the basis for algorithms in numerical quadrature (Simpson's rule) and numerical ordinary differential equations (multigrid methods).
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] In computer graphics, polynomials can be used to approximate complicated plane curves given a few specified points, for example the shapes of letters in typography.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] This is usually done with Bézier curves, which are a simple generalization of interpolation polynomials (having specified tangents as well as specified points).
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] In numerical analysis, polynomial interpolation is essential to perform sub-quadratic multiplication and squaring, such as Karatsuba multiplication and Toom–Cook multiplication, where interpolation through points on a product polynomial yields the specific product required.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] One may easily find points along *W*(*x*) at small values of *x*, and interpolation based on those points will yield the terms of *W*(*x*) and the specific product *ab*.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] As fomulated in Karatsuba multiplication, this technique is substantially faster than quadratic multiplication, even for modest-sized inputs, especially on parallel hardware.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] In computer science, polynomial interpolation also leads to algorithms for secure multi party computation and secret sharing.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] The theorem is also valid over any infinite field in place of the real numbers $\mathbb {R}$ , for example the rational or complex numbers.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] To prove uniqueness, assume that there exists another interpolating polynomial $q(x)$ of degree at most n , so that $p(x_{k})=q(x_{k})$ for all $k=0,\dotsc ,n$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Then $p(x)-q(x)$ is a polynomial of degree at most n which has $n+1$ distinct zeros (the $x_{k}$ ).
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] But a non-zero polynomial of degree at most n can have at most n zeros, so $p(x)-q(x)$ must be the zero polynomial, i.e. $p(x)=q(x)$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] An interpolant $p(x)$ corresponds to a solution $A=(a_{n},\ldots ,a_{0})$ of the above matrix equation $X\cdot A=Y$ .
