[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Several authors have therefore proposed algorithms which exploit the structure of the Vandermonde matrix to compute numerically stable solutions in O(*n*2) operations instead of the O(*n*3) required by Gaussian elimination.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] These methods rely on constructing first a Newton interpolation of the polynomial and then converting it to a monomial form.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] To find the interpolation polynomial *p*(*x*) in the vector space *P*(*n*) of polynomials of degree n, we may use the usual monomial basis for *P*(*n*) and invert the Vandermonde matrix by Gaussian elimination, giving a computational cost of O(*n*3) operations.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] To improve this algorithm, a more convenient basis for *P*(*n*) can simplify the calculation of the coefficients, which must then be translated back in terms of the monomial basis.
