[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] This suggests that we look for a set of interpolation nodes that makes *L* small.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] We conclude again that Chebyshev nodes are a very good choice for polynomial interpolation, as the growth in *n* is exponential for equidistant nodes.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] It is natural to ask, for which classes of functions and for which interpolation nodes the sequence of interpolating polynomials converges to the interpolated function as *n* → ∞?
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Convergence may be understood in different ways, e.g. pointwise, uniform or in some integral norm.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] The situation is rather bad for equidistant nodes, in that uniform convergence is not even guaranteed for infinitely differentiable functions.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] One classical example, due to Carl Runge, is the function *f*(*x*) = 1 / (1 + *x*2) on the interval [−5, 5].
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] The interpolation error || *f* − *pn*||∞ grows without bound as *n* → ∞.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Another example is the function *f*(*x*) = |*x*| on the interval [−1, 1], for which the interpolating polynomials do not even converge pointwise except at the three points *x* = ±1, 0.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] One might think that better convergence properties may be obtained by choosing different interpolation nodes.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] It is clear that the sequence of polynomials of best approximation $p_{n}^{*}(x)$ converges to *f*(*x*) uniformly (due to the Weierstrass approximation theorem).
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Now we have only to show that each $p_{n}^{*}(x)$ may be obtained by means of interpolation on certain nodes.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] But this is true due to a special property of polynomials of best approximation known from the equioscillation theorem.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Specifically, we know that such polynomials should intersect *f*(*x*) at least *n* + 1 times.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Choosing the points of intersection as interpolation nodes we obtain the interpolating polynomial coinciding with the best approximation polynomial.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] The defect of this method, however, is that interpolation nodes should be calculated anew for each new function *f*(*x*), but the algorithm is hard to be implemented numerically.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Does there exist a single table of nodes for which the sequence of interpolating polynomials converge to any continuous function *f*(*x*)?
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] The proof essentially uses the lower bound estimation of the Lebesgue constant, which we defined above to be the operator norm of *X**n* (where *X**n* is the projection operator on Π*n*).
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] For example, if equidistant points are chosen as interpolation nodes, the function from Runge's phenomenon demonstrates divergence of such interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Note that this function is not only continuous but even infinitely differentiable on [−1, 1].
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Runge's phenomenon shows that for high values of n, the interpolation polynomial may oscillate wildly between the data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] This problem is commonly resolved by the use of spline interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Here, the interpolant is not a polynomial but a spline: a chain of several polynomials of a lower degree.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Interpolation of periodic functions by harmonic functions is accomplished by Fourier transform.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] This can be seen as a form of polynomial interpolation with harmonic base functions, see trigonometric interpolation and trigonometric polynomial.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Hermite interpolation problems are those where not only the values of the polynomial *p* at the nodes are given, but also all derivatives up to a given order.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] This turns out to be equivalent to a system of simultaneous polynomial congruences, and may be solved by means of the Chinese remainder theorem for polynomials.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Birkhoff interpolation is a further generalization where only derivatives of some orders are prescribed, not necessarily all orders from 0 to a *k*.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] Collocation methods for the solution of differential and integral equations are based on polynomial interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] The technique of rational function modeling is a generalization that considers ratios of polynomial functions.
[src:interpolation-methods/polynomial-interpolation] At last, multivariate interpolation for higher dimensions.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, **Runge's phenomenon** (German: [ˈʁʊŋə]) is a problem of oscillation at the edges of an interval that occurs when using polynomial interpolation with polynomials of high degree over a set of equispaced interpolation points.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] It was discovered by Carl Runge when exploring the behavior of errors when using polynomial interpolation to approximate certain functions.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The discovery shows that going to higher degrees does not always improve accuracy.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The phenomenon is similar to the Gibbs phenomenon in Fourier series approximations.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Consider the case where one desires to interpolate through $n+1$ equispaced points of a function $f(x)$ using the n -degree polynomial $P_{n}(x)$ that passes through those points.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Naturally, one might expect from Weierstrass' theorem that using more points would lead to a more accurate reconstruction of $f(x)$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] However, this *particular* set of polynomial functions $P_{n}(x)$ is not guaranteed to have the property of uniform convergence; the theorem only states that a set of polynomial functions exists, without providing a general method of finding one.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The $P_{n}(x)$ produced in this manner may in fact diverge away from $f(x)$ as n increases; this typically occurs in an oscillating pattern that magnifies near the ends of the interpolation points.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The discovery of this phenomenon is attributed to Runge.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] (a scaled version of the Witch of Agnesi).
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] with a polynomial $P_{n}(x)$ of degree less than or equal to n , the resulting interpolation oscillates toward the end of the interval, i.e. close to $-1$ and 1 .
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] This shows that high-degree polynomial interpolation at equidistant points can be troublesome.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Runge's phenomenon is the consequence of two properties of this problem.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The phenomenon is graphically obvious because both properties combine to increase the magnitude of the oscillations.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] It is elementary to prove that with equidistant nodes, we have $W_{n}\leq n!h^{n+1}$ , where $h=2/n$ is the step size.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Moreover, assume that the $(n+1)$ -st derivative of f is bounded, i.e.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] But the magnitude of the $(n+1)$ -st derivative of Runge's function increases when n increases.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The consequence is that the resulting upper bound tends to infinity when n tends to infinity.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Although often used to explain the Runge phenomenon, the fact that the upper bound of the error goes to infinity does not necessarily imply, of course, that the error itself also diverges with n .
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] A standard example of such a set of nodes is Chebyshev nodes, for which the maximum error in approximating the Runge function is guaranteed to diminish with increasing polynomial order.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] When equidistant samples must be used because resampling on well-behaved sets of nodes is not feasible, the S-Runge algorithm can be considered.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] In this approach, the original set of nodes is mapped on the set of Chebyshev nodes, providing a stable polynomial reconstruction.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The peculiarity of this method is that there is no need of resampling at the mapped nodes, which are also called *fake nodes*.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The problem can be avoided by using spline curves which are piecewise polynomials.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] When trying to decrease the interpolation error one can increase the number of polynomial pieces which are used to construct the spline instead of increasing the degree of the polynomials used.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] One can also fit a polynomial of higher degree (for instance, with n points use a polynomial of order $N=n^{2}$ instead of $n+1$ ), and fit an interpolating polynomial whose first (or second) derivative has minimal $L^{2}$ norm.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] A similar approach is to minimize a constrained version of the $L^{p}$ distance between the polynomial's m -th derivative and the mean value of its m -th derivative.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] where $N\geq n-1$ and $m<N$ , with respect to the polynomial coefficients and the Lagrange multipliers, $\lambda _{i}$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] When $N=n-1$ , the constraint equations generated by the Lagrange multipliers reduce $P_{N}(x)$ to the minimum polynomial that passes through all n points.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] At the opposite end, $\lim _{N\to \infty }P_{N}(x)$ will approach a form very similar to a piecewise polynomials approximation.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] When $m=1$ , in particular, $\lim _{N\to \infty }P_{N}(x)$ approaches the linear piecewise polynomials, i.e. connecting the interpolation points with straight lines.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The role played by p in the process of minimizing $V_{p}$ is to control the importance of the size of the fluctuations away from the mean value.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The larger p is, the more large fluctuations are penalized compared to small ones.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The greatest advantage of the Euclidean norm, $p=2$ , is that it allows for analytic solutions and it guarantees that $V_{p}$ will only have a single minimum.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] When $p\neq 2$ there can be multiple minima in $V_{p}$ , making it difficult to ensure that a particular minimum found will be the global minimum instead of a local one.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Another method is fitting a polynomial of lower degree using the method of least squares.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Generally, when using m equidistant points, if $N<2{\sqrt {m}}$ then least squares approximation $P_{N}(x)$ is well-conditioned.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Using Bernstein polynomials, one can uniformly approximate every continuous function in a closed interval, although this method is rather computationally expensive.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] This method proposes to optimally stack a dense distribution of constraints of the type *P*″(*x*) = 0 on nodes positioned externally near the endpoints of each side of the interpolation interval, where P"(x) is the second derivative of the interpolation polynomial.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Those constraints are called External Fake Constraints as they do not belong to the interpolation interval and they do not match the behaviour of the Runge function.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] The method has demonstrated that it has a better interpolation performance than Piecewise polynomials (splines) to mitigate the Runge phenomenon.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] For every predefined table of interpolation nodes there is a continuous function for which the sequence of interpolation polynomials on those nodes diverges.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] For every continuous function there is a table of nodes on which the interpolation process converges.
[src:interpolation-methods/runge-s-phenomenon] Chebyshev interpolation (i.e., on Chebyshev nodes) converges uniformly for every absolutely continuous function.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] In mathematics, **trigonometric interpolation** is interpolation with trigonometric polynomials.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Interpolation is the process of finding a function which goes through some given data points.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] For trigonometric interpolation, this function has to be a trigonometric polynomial, that is, a sum of sines and cosines of given periods.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] This form is especially suited for interpolation of periodic functions.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] An important special case is when the given data points are equally spaced, in which case the solution is given by the discrete Fourier transform.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] (Note that we do *not* in general require these points to be equally spaced.) The interpolation problem is now to find coefficients such that the trigonometric polynomial *p* satisfies the interpolation conditions.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] The problem becomes more natural if we formulate it in the complex plane.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] We can rewrite the formula for a trigonometric polynomial as $p(x)=\sum _{k=-K}^{K}c_{k}e^{ikx},\,$ where *i* is the imaginary unit.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] This reduces the problem of trigonometric interpolation to that of polynomial interpolation on the unit circle.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Existence and uniqueness for trigonometric interpolation now follows immediately from the corresponding results for polynomial interpolation.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] For more information on formulation of trigonometric interpolating polynomials in the complex plane, see p.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] 156 of Interpolation using Fourier Polynomials.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Moreover, the interpolating polynomial is unique if and only if the number of adjustable coefficients is equal to the number of data points, i.e., *N* = 2*K* + 1.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] In the remainder of this article, we will assume this condition to hold true.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] The factor $e^{-iKx+iKx_{k}}$ in this formula compensates for the fact that the complex plane formulation contains also negative powers of $e^{ix}$ and is therefore not a polynomial expression in $e^{ix}$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] The correctness of this expression can easily be verified by observing that $t_{k}(x_{k})=1$ and that $t_{k}(x)$ is a linear combination of the right powers of $e^{ix}$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Here, the constants $\alpha _{k}$ can be chosen freely.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] This is caused by the fact that the interpolating function (**1**) contains an odd number of unknown constants.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] A common choice is to require that the highest frequency is of the form a constant times $\cos(Kx)$ , i.e. the $\sin(Kx)$ term vanishes, but in general the phase of the highest frequency can be chosen to be $\varphi _{K}$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Note that care must be taken in order to avoid infinities caused by zeros in the denominators.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Further simplification of the problem is possible if nodes $x_{m}$ are equidistant, i.e.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Further simplification by using (**4**) would be an obvious approach, but is obviously involved.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Note that $t_{k}(x)$ does not contain the $\sin {\tfrac {1}{2}}Nx$ as well.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Finally, note that the function $\sin {\tfrac {1}{2}}Nx$ vanishes at all the points $x_{m}$ .
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Multiples of this term can, therefore, always be added, but it is commonly left out.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] The special case in which the points *x**n* are equally spaced is especially important.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] The transformation that maps the data points *y**n* to the coefficients *a**k*, *b**k* is obtained from the discrete Fourier transform (DFT) of order N.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] (Because of the way the problem was formulated above, we have restricted ourselves to odd numbers of points.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] The case of the cosine-only interpolation for equally spaced points, corresponding to a trigonometric interpolation when the points have even symmetry, was treated by Alexis Clairaut in 1754.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] In this case the solution is equivalent to a discrete cosine transform.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] The sine-only expansion for equally spaced points, corresponding to odd symmetry, was solved by Joseph Louis Lagrange in 1762, for which the solution is a discrete sine transform.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] The full cosine and sine interpolating polynomial, which gives rise to the DFT, was solved by Carl Friedrich Gauss in unpublished work around 1805, at which point he also derived a fast Fourier transform algorithm to evaluate it rapidly.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Clairaut, Lagrange, and Gauss were all concerned with studying the problem of inferring the orbit of planets, asteroids, etc., from a finite set of observation points; since the orbits are periodic, a trigonometric interpolation was a natural choice.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Chebfun, a fully integrated software system written in MATLAB for computing with functions, uses trigonometric interpolation and Fourier expansions for computing with periodic functions.
[src:interpolation-methods/trigonometric-interpolation] Many algorithms related to trigonometric interpolation are readily available in Chebfun; several examples are available here.
